{
  "texts": [
    "Consequently, MeshCone scales efficiently with mesh resolution without sacrificing geometric fidelity.",
    "A.2 Solver Structure and Problem DimensionsIn 6 we included the configuration and structure of a Splitting Conic Solver optimization problem based on one of our meshes.",
    "The problem is made from 40,169 variables and 68,128 constraints, which makes it ideal for this type of optimizer that focuses on large problems.",
    "The Cone Structure part indicates the variables with no constraints in the primal formulation, which are 20,418, and the ones with linear constraints, which are 9,542.",
    "The SOC vars represent the variables subject to Second-Order Cone constraints (quadratic cone constraints of the form ∥x∥ ≤ t), totaling 38,168 variables organized into 4 blocks of 9,542 variables each.The nnz(A) and nnz(P) are the respective constraint matrix and cost matrix."
  ]
}